# Phase 1: Security Hardening — `v1.3.0` (Deep Dive)

> **Reviewer Role**: Senior WordPress + WooCommerce developer and Google Maps development expert (10+ years)

---

## 1.1 The Pricing Exploit (The Showstopper)

### Current Flow

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Browser as Customer Browser
    participant Frontend as Frontend JS
    participant WC as WooCommerce
    participant Backend as ALW_Shipping_Calculator

    Browser->>Frontend: User moves map pin
    Frontend->>Frontend: Calls Google Directions API (client-side)
    Frontend->>Frontend: Gets distance = 25.4 km
    Frontend->>Browser: Sets hidden field: billing_distance = 25.4
    Browser->>WC: Submits checkout form (POST)
    WC->>Backend: woocommerce_package_rates filter
    Backend->>Backend: Reads $_POST['billing_distance'] = 25.4
    Note over Backend: ⚠️ TRUSTS this value as Priority 1
    Backend->>Backend: Skips own server-side calculation
    Backend->>WC: Returns rate: 25 × ₹10 = ₹250
```

### The Exploit

A malicious user opens DevTools (or uses cURL/Postman) and does this:

```javascript
// In browser console, before clicking "Place Order":
document.querySelector('input[name="billing_distance"]').value = "0.5";
```

Or via cURL:
```bash
curl -X POST https://store.com/?wc-ajax=checkout \
  -d "billing_distance=0.5&billing_lat=28.6139&billing_lng=77.2090&..."
```

The vulnerable code in [class-alw-shipping.php:L39-L41](file:///d:/Z_Work/Sayan/sugar%20story/auto-location-woocommerce/includes/class-alw-shipping.php#L39-L41):

```php
// Priority 1: Use the Frontend Distance (Driving) if available
if ( $cust_dist > 0 ) {
    $distance_km = $cust_dist;  // Backend accepts 0.5 km — NO QUESTIONS ASKED
}
// Priority 2: Backend Calculation (Fail-safe) — NEVER REACHED
else { ... }
```

The backend sees `$cust_dist = 0.5`, which is `> 0`, so it **skips its own Directions API / Haversine calculation entirely**. Result: the customer gets free shipping (0.5 ≤ `ALW_FREE_KM`) even though they're actually 25 km away.

### The Fix

Invert the priority. The backend ALWAYS computes its own distance. The frontend value is **ignored for cost calculation**:

```php
// ALWAYS compute server-side — this is the authoritative distance
$dir = $this->get_directions_distance( ALW_STORE_LAT, ALW_STORE_LNG, $cust_lat, $cust_lng );

if ( $dir && isset( $dir['distance_km'] ) ) {
    $distance_km = (float) $dir['distance_km'];
} else {
    // Directions API failed — fall back to Haversine (straight-line)
    $distance_km = $this->get_haversine_km(
        (float) ALW_STORE_LAT, (float) ALW_STORE_LNG,
        (float) $cust_lat, (float) $cust_lng
    );
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The `$_POST['billing_distance']` value is ignored entirely for cost calculation. It can optionally be logged for debugging, but never used for pricing. Cross-checking (allowing frontend value if "close enough" to backend) is also inadvisable because even a ±20% tolerance can be gamed.

